[ECO "B33"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Lasker-Pelikan Variation, Sveshnikov Variation, Chelyabinsk Variation"]
[StudyName "Reddit Opening of the Week - Open Sicilian"]
[ChapterName "Sveshnikov"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/OCpFCD5c/GgDwimgn"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 { The Sveshnikov Variation
(named after Evgeny Sveshnikov, the man who dragged this opening out of the
depths), sometimes called the Pelikan or Chelyabinsk variation as well. The
move itself looks sort of gross - Black critically weakens the d5 and
d6-squares, but grabs his fair share of the center, something relatively rare
in the Sicilian. Only around the 70's & 80's did top level players begin to
respect the dynamic compensation Black receives for his weaknesses and
possibly wrecked kingside pawn structure. } 6. Ndb5! (6. Nf3 Bb4 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6e4] } 7. Bd3 d5! $36 { [%cal Gd5d4,Gd5e4] }) 6... d6 { [%csl Rd5,Rd6] } 7. Bg5! { This has
established itself as the only real try for an advantage, grabbing as much
control over d5 as possible, and giving White the option to fracture Black's
pawn structure with ...gxf6 later. } (7. Nd5!? { is possible,
forcing } { [%cal Rb5c7,Rc7a8] } 7... Nxd5 { , but this line has mostly been thrown to the curb, as
something like } 8. exd5 Nb8! { (the knight is better here, heading to d7 to
eventually stop white's ambitions of c4-c5) } 9. c4 Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O a6 12. Nc3 f5 $132 { of G.Oparin-P.Tregubov, European Championships 2014, is
acceptable for the second player. }) 7... a6 8. Na3 b5! { Black keeps White's knight out of c4, and incidentally threatens ...b4. This
is the main tabiya of the Sveshnikov, and the first real branching point for
White - does he take on f6 and wreck Black's pawn structure, or simply play
Nd5? } { [%cal Gb5b4,Ra3c4] } (8... Be6 { is not nearly as good, allowing White to fix his offside
a3-knight right away with } 9. Nc4! { , e.g. } 9... Rc8 10. Bxf6 gxf6 (10... Qxf6 11. Nb6! Rb8 12. Ncd5 Qd8 13. c3 $14 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Rc6d4] }) 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. Ne3 Bh6 13. Qf3 $14 { [%csl Gd5,Rd6,Re5,Rf6] }) 9. Nd5 (9. Bxf6 gxf6 (9... Qxf6? 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Bxb5! { is quite bad for Black, e.g. } 11... axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5+ 13. c3 Kd8 14. a4 Rb8 15. O-O Qa6 16. Qd3 { ->/+/- T.Hagen-H.Dewald,
Correspondence 2012 }) 10. Nd5 f5 { is another very critical and important main
line. White shatters Black's pawn structure, but in return gives him a host of
dynamic imbalances: the two bishops, a possibly imposing central pawn mass,
and the open g-file. A few examples that highlight the main options for White: } 11. Bd3 (11. Bxb5!? axb5 12. Nxb5 Ra4 (12... Ra7 { has also been played }) 13. Nbc7+ Kd7 { is a terrifying piece sacrifice that is practically but not
theoretically dangerous for Black! }) (11. c3 Bg7 (11... fxe4 12. Bxb5! axb5 13. Nxb5 { is close to fatal for
Black given that his two options used above don't work, e.g. } 13... Ra7 14. Nxa7 Nxa7 15. Qa4+ $18) 12. exf5 (12. Bd3 Be6 13. Nxb5!? axb5 14. Bxb5 Bd7 15. exf5 $13 { is a very popular piece sacrifice lately, recommended by Negi in his most
recent GM Repertoire book }) 12... Bxf5 13. Nc2 O-O 14. Nce3 Be6 15. Bd3 f5 16. O-O { was recommended for White in "Experts vs. the Sicilian" a long time ago,
but nowadays Black scores well after the prophylactic } 16... Kh8!) 11... Be6 12. O-O (12. Qh5 Rg8 13. g3 { was once quite popular and topical, but either 13...
Rc8 or } 13... Nd4 $132 { , a la "The Easiest Sicilian", give Black good play }) 12... Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne7 { has historically been the main line, with two important
options for White: } 14. c3 (14. Nxb5!? { but Black has historically secured adequate counterplay, e.g. } 14... Bg7 15. Nc3 e4 16. Bc4 O-O 17. Qd2 Ng6 18. Bb3 Re8 19. f4 Qb6+ 20. Kh1 e3 21. Qe2 Bxc3 22. bxc3 $44 { R.Langeveld-M.Voss, Correspondence
2012 } { [%csl Rb3,Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gb6c5] }) 14... Bg7 15. Qh5 e4 16. Bc2 O-O 17. Rae1 Qc8 $13 { J.Tanti-T.Geier, Correspondence 2014 } { [%cal Gc8c5,Gc8f5,Yg6e5,Rf2f3] }) 9... Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 { [%csl Gd5] } 11. c3 { White starts the tedious journey of his knight back to the center
(usually e3) and will generally prepare a4 to start chipping away at Black's
far advanced queenside pawns. In turn, Black will play ...Bg5 to meet the
knight on e3 head-on, and will start to wear away at White's control of the
d5-square with ...Ne7, ...Be6, and ...f5, usually prepared by ...Kh8 first. } { [%cal Ga3c2,Gc2e3,Ya2a4,Gf6g5,Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Yc6e7] } (11. c4!? b4 12. Nc2 O-O { has been extremely popular lately - White continues
to search for a small edge here, and has three options for his light squared
bishop: e2 or h3, with or without tossing in h4 first (which stops ...Bg5). An
example of each: } 13. g3 (13. Be2 a5 14. O-O Bg5 15. Qd3 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Ga1d1,Gf1d1,Gd3d6] } 15... Be6 16. Rad1 Ra7!? { [%cal Gc6b8,Yb8a6,Ya6c5,Yb8d7,Yd7c5] } 17. b3 Rd7 18. Bf3 Nb8 19. a3 bxa3 20. Nxa3 Na6 21. Nb5?! Bxd5 22. cxd5? (22. exd5 f5 $15) 22... Rb7 23. Be2 Qb8 24. Ra1?! Nb4 25. Qc3 Rxb5 26. Bxb5 Qxb5 $19 { Zhao
Jun-Wei Yi, Zaozhuang 2015 }) 13... Bg5! { (Black sneaks this in before h4) } 14. Bg2 (14. h4 Bh6 15. Bh3 Be6! { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gh3e6,Gf7e6] } 16. Kf1 a5 17. Kg2 Nb8! { [%cal Gb8d7,Gd7c5] } 18. Bf5 Nd7 19. Nce3 g6 20. Qg4 Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Bxe6 Bxe3 23. fxe3 fxe6 24. Raf1 Qe7 25. h5 g5 26. h6 Rxf1 27. Rxf1 Rf8 28. Rxf8+ Kxf8 29. Qf3+ Qf7 { ½-½ M.Rüfenacht-D.Fleetwood,
Correspondence 2015 }) 14... a5 15. O-O Ne7 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qd3 Be6 18. b3 Ra6 19. h4 Bh6 20. a3 bxa3 21. Nxa3 Qa7 22. Nb5 Qc5 23. Rfd1 Rd8 24. Qc3 Rda8 $14 { was slightly better for White in S.Karjakin-Y.Yangyi, World Team
Championships 2015, but the Russian was unable to make progress and agreed to
a draw a few moves later. }) 11... O-O 12. Nc2 Bg5 { The
following 8-12 moves are generally rattled off without much thought - nowadays,
once White has decided that they're going for 11.c3 and not 12.c4, he has
little choice if he's searching for an opening advantage. } { [%cal Rc2e3,Gg5e3] } 13. a4! bxa4! (13... Rb8?! { has not scored well in practice - it seems as though Black
should prefer the weak pawn to be on a5 instead, e.g. } 14. axb5 axb5 15. Bd3 Be6 16. Ncb4 Nxb4 17. Nxb4 Qd7 18. O-O g6 19. Qe2 $14 { A.Wiwe-J.
Rendboe, Denmark Team Championships 2014 } { [%csl Gb5] }) 14. Rxa4 { [%csl Ra6] } 14... a5 15. Bc4 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4g8] } (15. Bb5 { was once popular, but } 15... Ne7! { is obvious
and adequate. }) 15... Rb8 { [%csl Gb8][%cal Gb8b2] } 16. b3 (16. Ra2!? { is also
an important move. }) 16... Kh8 { [%cal Gf7f5,Rc4g8] } 17. Nce3 Ne7! (17... g6!? { was once in vogue, but fell off the face of the Earth
after Shirov took a massive beating in the pawn-sac line to Giri, who's always
at the forefront of opening theory. The following moves are sort of forced to
a point: } { [%cal Gf7f5,Re3f5] } 18. h4! Bxh4 { (else simply h5) } 19. g3 Bg5 20. f4 exf4 21. gxf4 Bh4+ 22. Kf1! { [%csl Rh7][%cal Ga4a2,Ga2h2,Gh2h7] } 22... f5 23. Ra2! fxe4 24. Rah2 g5 25. Qh5 Rb7 (25... Ne5 { is probably a better
defensive move and has been tried in a few correspondence games, but Black is
still clearly in a lot of trouble, e.g. } { [%cal Ge5c4,Ge5f3] } 26. Ke2 Nxc4 27. fxg5 Rxb3 28. Rxh4 Rb2+ 29. Ke1 $16 { /-> D.Lafarga Santorromán-A.Voll, Correspondence
2012 }) 26. Ke2 Be6 27. Qh6 Bg8 28. Rg2 Rbf7 29. Rxh4 gxh4 30. Nf5 { [%cal Gf5h4] } 30... h3 31. Nh4 Qxh4 32. Rxg8+ Rxg8 33. Qxh4 $18 { A.Giri-A.Shirov,
Hoogeveen 2014 }) 18. Nxe7 Qxe7 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. O-O f5! 21. exf5 Bxf5 22. Qe2 Bd7 (22... Be6 { is also possible. }) 23. Ra2 Be6 24. Rd1 Rc8 { E.Riccio-A.Nickel, Correspondence 2007. There have been about 80
or so correspondence games from this position, and White has made little
progress. Optically his position looks great - Black has weak pawns on a5 and
d6, three pawn islands to White's two, and look at that steed on d5. But after
an eventual (and inevitable!) exchange on d5, we're left with opposite colored
bishops. Black will complete the more typical Kalashnikov maneuver with ...
Bd8-b6 and after that, his rooks will be active, putting pressure on f2 and
White's queenside pawns. } { [%cal Gd8d7,Yg5d8,Ge6d5] } *


[Event "Reddit Opening of the Week - Open Sicilian: Kalashnikov"]
[Date "2016.01.07"]
[White "Kalashnikov"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Tony Rotella"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B32"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Kalashnikov Variation"]
[StudyName "Reddit Opening of the Week - Open Sicilian"]
[ChapterName "Kalashnikov"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/OCpFCD5c/ovGXAOCw"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 { The move that signals the
Kalashnikov. Just as in the Sveshnikov, Black accepts a critically weak
d5-square and a backwards d6-pawn in exchange for an equal share of the center,
a possible counter-weakness on d4, the plan of a beneficial piece exchange
with ...Be7-g5 and dynamic chances with ...d5 or ...f5 down the road. A
critical difference between the Sveshnikov and Kalashnikov is that because ...
Nf6 and Nc3 are not immediately inserted, White doesn't generally get to
enhance his control over the d5-square with Bg5xf6. However, Black doesn't
force White to block the c-pawn either, and so White gains the option to push
c4. } 5. Nb5 { This is by far the best move, forcing ...d6 to a
certain extent. The other moves allow Black too much counterplay, and usually
the ...d5-break, for example: } { [%cal Rb5d6] } (5. Nf5 Nf6 (5... d5! { right away is good as
well, e.g. } 6. Qxd5! Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. cxd3 O-O-O { M.Khachiyan-M.Adams, Chicago Open 2010 }) 6. Nc3 d5! { (the odd
position of White's knight on f5 is exploited) } 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Qf3 Qd7 10. Bg5 e4 11. Qe2 Bb4!? { (The Killer Sicilian) }) (5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 7. Bd3 d5! 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Bd2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 $15 { [%csl Rc2,Rc3,Ge5] }) (5. Nb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Bd3 d5! { is similar to 5.Nf3
above. }) 5... d6 { [%csl Rd5,Rd6] } (5... a6 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd1 Qg6 9. Nc3 Nge7) 6. c4 { This is an important difference between the Sveshnikov &
Kalashnikov - since Black didn't force Nc3 White can clamp down on the
d5-square with c4. It's not all advantage for him though - his light-squared
bishop is now fairly bad, and c4 is not a developing move. The main strategic
goals for Black are to exchange off his bad Bf8 for White's good Bc1 and to
enforce a pawn break that shakes up White's center a bit - usually ...b5, but
occasionally ...f5 as well. White would simply like to avoid exchanges and
smother Black with his extra space. } { [%csl Gc1,Yc4,Rd4,Rd5,Yd6,Ye4,Ye5,Rf8][%cal Gf8e7,Ge7g5,Gb7b5] } (6. N1c3 a6 7. Na3 Be7!? { This is the
newest way to play the Kalashnikov, though now less surprising than when I
started my book. Black doesn't keep White's knight from hopping back into the
center via the less laborious c4-route, but he does avoid the immediate
weakening of his queenside as in 7...b5 below, while avoiding Bg5. } (7... b5 { [%cal Gb5b4,Ra3c4] } 8. Nd5 Nge7 { is the older main line, but practice has
shown that it's not totally easy to keep Black's queenside intact after } (8... Nce7 9. c4! Nxd5 10. exd5 bxc4 11. Nxc4 Nf6 12. Be3 Rb8 13. Be2 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. a4 $14) 9. c4! { , e.g. } 9... Nxd5 (9... Nd4 10. cxb5 Nxd5 11. exd5 { transposes }) 10. exd5! { (White keeps the tension on the queenside, inducing
concessions or winning a pawn) } (10. cxd5 Nd4 (10... Ne7 11. Bd3 Ng6) 11. Be3 g6!? 12. Bxd4 (12. Bd3 Bg7 13. O-O O-O) 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bg7 { [%cal Gf7f5] }) 10... Nd4 11. cxb5 Bd7! (11... Be7 { is older
still, and likely worse }) 12. Be3 (12. bxa6 Qa5+) 12... axb5 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Bd3 (14. Qxd4 Be7! 15. Be2 (15. Qxg7 Bf6 16. Qg3 Bxb2 $19) 15... Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Bf6 $15) 14... Qa5+ { V.Costa Trillo-J.Lecha González, Correspondence 2014 was
an absolute mess, but just about playable for Black. See "The Complete
Kalashnikov" by Cornette and Libiszewski for more info here if interested. } 15. Kf1) 8. Nc4! { [%cal Rc1e3,Rc4b6,Re3b6] } (8. Nd5 Nf6 { is basically an
improved Sveshnikov for Black, trading the weakening ...b5 for the developing .
..Be7. } 9. Nxf6+ (9. Bd3 Nxd5 10. exd5 Qa5+) 9... Bxf6 10. Nc4 O-O 11. Be3 (11. Nxd6 Be6 12. c3 Qc7 13. Nc4 Rfd8 14. Qc2 b5 15. Ne3 Rac8 16. Be2 Qa5 $44) (11. Qxd6 Qxd6 12. Nxd6 Nb4 13. Bd3 Rd8) 11... Nd4!) (8. Be3!? Nf6 9. Nc4 b5 10. Nb6 Rb8 11. Nxc8 Qxc8! 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O b4 14. Nd5 Nxe4 15. a3 $44 { of A.Morozevich-T.Radjabov, Zug 2013, is also a popular try for an advantage
these days - White has good compensation for the pawn. }) 8... b5 (8... Nf6 9. Bg5!) 9. Ne3 { [%csl Rd5] } 9... Nf6 { [%cal Gb5b4,Gf6e4] } 10. g3 { White goes for
maximum control of the d5-square. } (10. Bd3 { is an obvious enough move,
kicking off another main line, e.g. } 10... O-O 11. O-O Rb8! { Not easy move to
understand at first. Perhaps the most important point is that if Black played
the more obvious 11...Be6 instead, he would not be able to trade
knight-for-knight when White responds with 12.Ned5, he'd have to give up the
light-squared bishop, which would be a fairly large concession. Black also
guards the weak b6-square and preempts White's attempts at attacking on the
queenside with a4. An example of typical play here is } 12. Ncd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bg5! { (Black completes the usual plan of exchanging off her bad bishop) } 14. c3 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Be6 16. a4 Bxd5 17. exd5 Ne7 18. axb5 axb5 { [%csl Rb5,Gd5][%cal Gg7g6,Gf7f5,Ge5e4,Yg8g7,Ye7g8,Yg8f6,Yd8b6,Yb6b7,Rd1e2,Rc1a1,Ra1a5,Ra5a7] } 19. f4 Qb6+ { T.Abrahamyan-I.Krush, US Women's Championship 2014 }) 10... O-O 11. Bg2 b4 12. Ncd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bg5! { The usual
stuff by now. } { [%csl Gc1,Rd6,Re5,Rg5] } 14. Bxg5 Qxg5 15. O-O { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rd5c7,Rc7a8,Rd1d6] } 15... Rb8! { Black
preempts the threat of Nc7 and Qxd6 by moving the rook out of the way. He also
simultaneously allows his knight to hop into d4 without hanging the b4 pawn
and preempts White's a3 strike by allowing ...a5. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Gc8e6,Ge6d5,Ga6a5,Ra2a3,Rd1d3,Ra1d1,Rf2f4,Rf4f6] } 16. Qd3 { [%cal Gd3a6,Rc8e6] } 16... a5 17. a3 Be6 18. axb4 axb4 (18... Nxb4 { S.Karjakin-T.Radjabov, World
Blitz Championships 2012 }) 19. Ra6 Rfc8 20. c3 Qd8! { Black returns his queen
to the center/queenside, perfectly harmonizing his pieces. } 21. Rd1 g6 22. Ne3 Rb6 23. h4 h5 { I.Nepomniachtchi-V.Ivanchuk, Tal Memorial 2011 }) 6... Be7! { Black avoids Bg5 and also waits for N1c3 before kicking the knight back,
since then it will have to go to the poor a3-square. } 7. N1c3 { There are other
moves, but this natural choice is the main one. } (7. Be2) (7. b3) (7. Bd3) 7... a6 8. Na3 { [%csl Ra3] } 8... f5!? { This is the more aggressive and dynamic option.
Black accepts some extra-weak light squares and a three pawn island to two
disadvantage for free, active development and open lines for his pieces. } (8... Be6 { [%csl Gc1,Re7][%cal Ge7g5] } 9. Nc2! (9. Be2 Nd4! { allows Black to
ease his spacial disadvantage somewhat, grabbing the two bishops and
exchanging off a set of minor pieces }) 9... Rc8 { Black wants to move his
knight and attack c4, since protecting it with b3 leaves the knight loose on
b3 after ...b5! } 10. Be2! (10. b3 Nf6 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O b5! 13. cxb5 Na7! { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8c3,Ya7b5] } 14. Bb2 Nxb5 15. Nxb5 axb5 { [%csl Ge4] } 16. Bd3 Qb6 { S.Pastrana Alvarez-A.Jankowiak, Correspondence 2008 }) 10... Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. Be3 Nb8! $132 { is another important main line given in my
book. }) 9. exf5 (9. Bd3 { is also common, but allows } 9... f4! { , changing the
structure into something that's likely a bit easier for Black to deal with
than the main line. His extra space on the kingside will grant him reasonable
attacking chances. White's idea is linked with breaking down the chain
immediately with } 10. g3 Nf6! (10... fxg3 11. hxg3 Nf6 12. Nc2 O-O 13. Nd5 $14 { is clearly more comfortable for him }) 11. gxf4 exf4 12. Bxf4 O-O { [%cal Gf6g4,Gf8f2] } 13. Bg3 Ng4?! (13... Bh3! { is the correct way for Black to gain sufficient counterplay }) 14. Be2? (14. f4! { gives White a clear edge }) 14... Nxf2!! { Likely all
preparation, but this game from Nataf is too good to not add in! } 15. Qd5+ Kh8 16. Bxf2 Nb4! (16... Rxf2 17. Kxf2 Bh4+?? 18. Kg2 Nb4 19. Qd2 { as Black's queen finds it
hard to join the attack without hopping out to g5 }) 17. Qh5 (17. Qd2 Rxf2! 18. Kxf2 Bg5! 19. Qd1 Bh4+ 20. Kg2 Qg5+ { is fatal }) 17... Rxf2! 18. Kxf2 Bh4+ 19. Kg2 g6! 20. Qf3 Qg5+ 21. Kf1 Bh3+!! { A wonderful
clearance sacrifice! } { [%cal Ga8f8] } 22. Qxh3 Rf8+ 23. Bf3 Qe3 24. Qxh4 Nd3! { Nataf is
renowned for his attacking skills - instead of bagging the piece right away,
he brings the final piece into the fray. It's actually mate in 7. } 25. Nd5 Qxf3+ (25... Rxf3+ 26. Kg2 Qe2+ 27. Kg1 g5!! { deflecting the queen from f2 with mate in a few }) 26. Kg1 Nf2 27. Kf1 Qxh1+ 28. Ke2 Qxa1 { and the venerable author, mathematician, and amateur astronomer
packed it up in the game J.Nunn-I.Nataf, French Team Championships 1999. }) 9... Bxf5 { [%csl Ra6,Rb7,Gd5,Rd6,Re5,Rg7,Rh7][%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8,Gf1d3,Ga3c2,Gc2e3] } 10. Bd3! { A trade of light-squared bishops will only serve to accentuate
Black's weaknesses on that color complex and his structural problems in
general. } 10... Be6! { Black obviously declines. } 11. O-O Nf6 12. Nc2 O-O 13. Ne3 { [%csl Rd5] } 13... Qd7 { [%cal Ge7d8,Gd8b6,Ya8c8,Yc8e8] } 14. Ned5 Rae8 (14... Bd8!?) 15. Be3 Bd8 $13 { M.Bluvshtein-I.Nataf, Montreal 2005 } *


