1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 { To review, White basically has the choice between posting up the bishop
on a slightly more active square which also stops ...d5 (but takes a tempo and
leaves the bishop somewhat more vulnerable), or castling long right away,
which allows the thematic and much desired ...d5-break. } { [%csl Gg7] } 9. Bc4 (9. O-O-O { [%cal Gc6d4,Gc8d7] } 9... d5! { Black can and should get this, as the alternatives are pretty bad as of now. } { [%cal Gc1b1] } 10. exd5 (10. Nxc6!? { This very direct idea is becoming very trendy actually,
and it's quite dangerous. } 10... bxc6 11. Bh6 { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] } 11... Bxh6 { This is the most combative,
deflecting White's queen away from the center and queenside. } 12. Qxh6 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 12... Rb8!? { [%cal Gh2h4] } (12... e5 { Giri's recommendation, e.g. } 13. exd5 cxd5 14. h4 d4 15. h5 Be6 16. hxg6 fxg6 17. Ne4 Qc7 18. Bd3 Bf5 $13 { K.Griffith - J.Liang, New York 2021 }) 13. e5 (13. h4 Qa5 14. e5 (14. h5 Rxb2! 15. hxg6 fxg6 16. Kxb2 Qb4+ 17. Kc1 Qxc3 18. e5 Qa3+ 19. Kd2 Qa5+ { draws }) (14. a3!? { M.Nayhebaver - M.Hrabusa,
Slovakian Championship 2019, avoids the draw with ...Rb2 and keeps the game
quite complex. }) 14... Nh5 15. Bd3 Qb4 16. g4 Qf4+ 17. Qxf4 Nxf4 18. Ne2 Nxd3+ 19. Rxd3 Ba6 20. Rd2 Bxe2 21. Rxe2 e6) 13... Nd7 14. Rd4! { White very
cleverly seeks to swing the rook over to h4! } { [%cal Gd4h4] } 14... Re8 { [%cal Gd7f8] } 15. e6 fxe6 16. Bd3 Nf8 17. h4 e5 { [%cal Gh4h5] } 18. Ra4 (18. h5 exd4 19. hxg6 Qd6 { [%cal Gd6h6] } 20. gxh7+ Kh8 21. Qg7+! Kxg7 22. h8=Q+ Kf7 23. Rh7+ Nxh7 24. Qxh7+ Kf8 25. Qh8+ Kf7 26. Qh7+ $10) 18... Qd6 19. h5 Bf5 { of A.Fier - M.Perunovic, Belgrade 2021, holds it all together. }) (10. Kb1 Nxd4 11. e5 Nf5 12. exf6 Bxf6 (12... exf6) 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 Nxe3 15. Qd2 Nxd1) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 { [%cal Ge3d4] } 12. Bd4 { This is the most annoying line for Black, shattering his
queenside structure then neutralizing the strong bishop along the long
diagonal. } (12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Qxd5 Qc7) 12... e5 { Historically, this has been the main choice and is also the
most combative. } (12... Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Qb6 14. Bc4!? (14. Na4 { is the normal
move here } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb6a5,Gb6c7] } 14... Qa5!? { [%cal Ge7e5,Gd4a4] } (14... Qc7 15. Bc4 (15. Nc5!? { right away is also a good try }) 15... Rd8 { [%cal Gc4b3,Ga4c5] } 16. Nc5 (16. Bb3 { is also playable, and after } 16... Be6 17. Nc5 Nf4 18. Nxe6 Nxe6 19. Qe3 Nf4 { of S.Rublevsky - V.Cmilyte, European Championships 2011,
play is somewhat similar to our main line with 14...Qa5!? }) 16... Bf5 { [%cal Gf5c2] } 17. Bb3 Nf4 $13 { [%cal Gd8d4] } 18. Qf2 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 $10 { [%cal Gd1d8,Gd1e1] }) 15. b3 { [%csl Gb3][%cal Gc4b3,Gc8e6] } 15... Qc7 (15... Be6!? { was recommended
by Jones in his GM Repertoire book and also looks generally playable for Black. } 16. Qe5) 16. Bc4 Rd8 17. g4 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8f5] } (17. Rhe1 { [%cal Gc7h2] } 17... Bf5 (17... Qxh2!? $146) 18. Qe5 Qxe5 19. Rxe5 Bxc2 20. Rd2 (20. Kxc2 Nb4+ 21. Kc3 Nxa2+ 22. Kc2 Nb4+ $10) 20... Bf5 21. Bxd5 cxd5 22. Rxe7 { M.Corallo - M.Bodek, US Masters 2014 } 22... d4 $10 { [%csl Ra4][%cal Ra4c3] }) 17... Be6 18. Nc5 { [%cal Gc5e6] } 18... Nf4 { [%cal Gd8d4] } 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 20. Qe4 Ng5 21. Qe3 Nh3! { [%csl Gh3,Gf4][%cal Gh3f4] } 22. Rhe1 e6 23. Kb2 Nf4 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Qe5 Qxe5+ 26. Rxe5 Nd5 { A.Savoca - L.
Parsons, Correspondence 2021 }) 14... Ne3 15. Rd2 Qxd4 16. Rxd4 Nxg2 (16... Bf5!? 17. Bb3 Nxg2 18. Rg1 e5! 19. Rc4 Nf4 20. Re1 Be6! 21. Rxc6 Bxb3 22. axb3 Ne6! 23. Rxe5 Nd4 24. Rc4 Nxf3 25. Re3 Ng5) 17. Re4! $14 { E.Safarli -V.
Asadli, Azerbaijan Championships 2021 }) (12... Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Bh6+ 14. Be3 Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3 Qb6 { [%cal Ge3e7] } 16. Qxe7 Be6 17. Qa3 { [%cal Ga8d8] } 17... Rad8 (17... Rfd8 18. Bd3 Rd5 19. Rhe1 Ra5 20. Qc3 Rxa2 21. b3 Ra5 { G.Gopal - S.Narayanan, Indian Championships 2009 } 22. Kb2 $146 { +/- }) 18. Bd3 Rd5 19. Rhe1! { [%cal Gf8d8] } 19... Ra5 20. Qc3 Rxa2 21. b3! { [%cal Gc4g8,Gc3h8] } 21... Ra5 { [%cal Ga5d5] } 22. Kb2 { [%cal Ga5d5] } (22. Rxe6!? fxe6 23. Bc4) 22... Rc5 (22... Rd5 23. Bc4 $14 { S.Fedorchuk - A.
Timofeev, European Championships 2009 } (23. Ra1 $14 { K.Arakhamia Grant - I.
Gaponenko, European Women's Cup 2009 })) 23. Qf6 { +/-/+/= } 23... a5?? 24. Rxe6! fxe6 25. Qxe6+ Rf7 26. Bc4 Rxc4 27. Qxc4 Qc7 28. Re1 Qxh2 29. Re7 Qf4 30. Qxf7+ Qxf7 31. Rxf7 Kxf7 32. Ka3 $18 { D.Lintchevski - A.Kashlinskaya, Russian Team
Championships 2009 }) 13. Bc5 { [%cal Gc8e6] } 13... Re8!? { Moving the rook right away has become the
main choice lately - Black reasons that after 13...Be6 they'll have to move
the rook eventually, so why not do it now and remain more flexible with your
other pieces. } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gc8e6] } (13... Be6 14. Ne4 (14. Bxf8 Qxf8 $44) 14... Re8 15. h4 h6 (15... h5!?) 16. g4 (16. h5!? g5 { [%cal Gg2g4] } 17. c4!? (17. g4) 17... Qc7 (17... Nb6 18. Qc3 $16) 18. Ba3 (18. cxd5?? cxd5 $19) 18... Nf6 19. Nxg5! e4! (19... hxg5? 20. h6 Bh8 21. Qxg5+ Kh7 22. Bd3+ $18) 20. Bd6 Qb7 21. Nxe6 Rxe6 22. Qb4 { +/=/+/- A.Parushev - D.
Dushkin, Correspondence 2019 }) 16... Qc7 17. h5! (17. g5 h5 18. Bc4 Red8 19. Qf2 { [%csl Gh4,Gg5] }) 17... g5 { [%csl Rg7,Gf3,Gg4,Gh5] } 18. Bc4 Red8 19. Qf2 $16 { Z.Sanner - A.Larsen, Correspondence 2020. Black's kingside majority is not in
great shape, and in contrast to 17.g5, White won't have to worry about a weak
h4-pawn in the endgame. } { [%cal Gf7f5] }) 14. Ne4 (14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Rxd5 Be6 { [%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] } 17. Rd6 (17. Rd3 Bf5! (17... Bxa2 18. Ra3 Be6 19. Ba6! $16) 18. Ra3 Rec8 { [%cal Gb2b4,Ga7a5] } 19. Ra5 (19. b4 a5 $132) 19... Bh6+ 20. Kb1 Bf8 $44 { Y.Malinarski - T.Slisser,
Hoogeveen 2003 }) 17... Bxa2 18. b3 Rec8 19. Rd5 a5 20. Kb2 a4 21. Kxa2 axb3+ 22. Kxb3 Ra5 23. Bc4 (23. Kb4 Raxc5 24. Rxc5 Bf8) 23... Raxc5 24. Rxc5 Rxc5 { E.Gufeld - S.Kudrin, Hastings 1986 }) 14... Qc7 15. h4 f5 16. Nd6 Rd8 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 18. h5 Nb6 19. Bxb6 Rxd2 20. Bc4+ Kf8 21. Bxc7 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rxc7 23. hxg6 Bh6+ 24. Kb1 hxg6 25. Rd6 { [%cal Gd6c6,Gd6g6] } 25... Kg7 26. b4 $14 { D.Swiercz - D.Naroditsky, US
Championships 2021 }) (9. g4 Be6 10. Nxe6 fxe6) 9... Bd7 (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 { Giri's recommendation -
